17/02/19, 8:45 pm - Sweta Sahu: Jyaadaaa pataaho
17/02/19, 8:46 pm - Sweta Sahu: Hello friends, 

Any one from channel sales or fmcg sector, unilever,  p&g etc, kindly let know the reverse logistics process,  of damage and expired goods,  
Where those stocks goes? 
How the reimbursement work out? 
Whats the logistics part of it ?

Kindly guide for same... 

Thanks
17/02/19, 8:46 pm - Sweta Sahu: He sent this to his friends colleagues
17/02/19, 8:46 pm - Sweta Sahu: From cement manufacturing industry channel sales network 


We sent 3 invoice copy and POD copy...one for transporter and rest 2 are for buyer and seller.. 
Buyer must write the quantity (in case of ours, it is bag)  received in invoice and pod.
Also we follow an application called E-POD.. 
If any shortage or damage return,  buyer confirms it in manual challan or POD and also confirm stocks received in mobile ..
Buyer gives confirmation in both manual as well as mobile app through his stamp and duly sign.

We have bill cycle process of transporter Every 10days I. E 10th,  20th and 30th through hard copy deposit of POD slips.. 
So generally it takes 10days to settle the damage and shortage.. 

But if sales people want immediate resolution, sales team inform logistics and accounts with either buyer hard-copy or scan copy,  it generally resolves within a week.. 

We are not 100% ePOD yet,  that is the reason we follow manual entry also..
